      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>During the mid-20th century, there was increasingly widespread popularity of  various forms
            of African American music, resulting in previously unrecognized African American artists
            and musicians being brought into mainstream media. Many groups and individual musicians
            became commercial successes in the genres of jazz, rhythm and blues, and within the
            newly developing genre of rock and roll. There was also increased popularity of hard
            blues in the 1950s, as well as doo-wop, a style involving different vocal parts, simple
            lyrics and little to no instrumentation. In 1959, the creation of Motown Records allowed
            many African American artists to achieve mainstream success through a new style of soul
            music infused with pop elements, cementing the importance and influence of African
            Americans in the development of music style and history. </p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">African American Musicians Photograph Collection</emph> consists
            of 76 professional head shots and photographs of various African American musicians,
            performers and singers that were primarily active during the 1950s and 1960s.</p>
         <p>There are also advertising biographies about Bobby Bland, Donald Byrd and Eddie
            Kendricks alongside their respective photographs.</p>
      </scopecontent>
